ce:section.ce:para:
Fig. 8
 elucidates the stress–strain curve explaining the mechanical properties of g-CDs decorated PVA composite films. The tensile properties vary as the g-CDs get embedded into the PVA and act as nanofillers in the matrix. Lower weight percentages of g-CDs do not much alter the tensile strength of the matrix. However, increase in the g-CD concentration changes the properties (Table 2
). The stress–strain curve clearly indicates an increase in the elongation at break strain as the g-CD content increases (up to 15 wt%). It is also interesting to note that very high percentages of g-CDs lead to a drop in the tensile properties. Maximum elongation at break strain of 123 % is observed for PVA with 10 wt% of g-CDs. Ultimate tensile strength values increase slightly with an increase in g-CD content up to 15 wt% and maximum tensile strength of 36 MPa is observed for PVA which has 15 wt% g-CDs. A higher level of stress achieved with an increase in g-CDs content is a consequence of the fact that g-CDs are properly reinforced into the host matrix [54]. Elastic modulus or Young’s Modulus which is the ratio of tensile stress to the tensile strain is maximum for the film with 15 wt% g-CDs beyond which the tensile strength decreases abruptly. The elastic nature increases initially as g-CDs get incorporated in the host matrix but decreases beyond 10 wt% of g-CDs. The initial increase in the elastic nature might be attributed to the fact that g-CDs interrupt the hydrogen bonding in PVA facilitating the molecular motion of polymer chains making it less crystalline. The area under the stress–strain curve defines the toughness of the material which is the energy required to break the films. The toughness is also found to increase upon the incorporation of g-CDs compared to neat PVA. Maximum toughness was also observed for the 15 wt% g-CDs integrated PVA matrix. The sharp reduction in the mechanical properties of the films at very high concentrations of g-CDs (20 wt% and 25 wt%) might be attributed to the fact that the film formation becomes harder at very high g-CD concentration as there is aggregation of nanofillers in the matrix which leads to non-uniform distribution of g-CDs in PVA resulting in more water uptake, swelling and easily breakable films.
